<dl id="n26140b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26140b">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26140b"> 140(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> at 1 glance ( priest left host / boats pass / ship under full sail / salmon killed with a spear / hunter pursuing a doe <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n26140b"><li>FW 139.02 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/lexfa.htm#n26140b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/l39fa.htm#n26140b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n26140b">MS BL 47473-186</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:052 <a name="f11d" href="../../FF/fdra/fda.htm#f11d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/f/f11d.htm#n26140b">Draft: I.6&sect;1.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Hardiman, in his History of Galway, tells of an Italian traveller of those days being at Mass in a private house in Galway, &ldquo;saw, at one view the Blessed Sacrament in the hands of the priest, boats passing up and down the river, a ship entering the port in full sail, a salmon killed with a spear, and hunters and hounds pursuing a deer; upon which he observed that, although he had travelled the greater part of Europe, he had never before witnessed a sight which combined so much variety and beauty.&rdquo; <small> Terence O'Hanlon, [SI29may27]&ldquo;The Proud Past of Galway&rdquo; <cite a>Sunday Independent</cite></a> (29 May 1927) 5/7</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: This <cite>Sunday Independent</cite> article is based on material from Hardiman&apos;s <a name= JHHT2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JHHT2"><cite>History of Galway</cite></a>. </mm> </dd></dl>
